      <div id="inner-3-lab" class="inner-panel active">
        <p class="slide-sub" style="margin-bottom:16px">A T-shaped approach: deep on what falls directly under store responsibility, broad on the upstream decisions that drive store costs. Both matter — and most consultants only do one.</p>
        <div class="approach-ab">
          <div class="approach-point">
            <div class="ap-badge ap-badge-a" style="transform:rotate(-90deg)">↓</div>
            <div>
              <div class="ap-header"><span class="ap-keyword">OUT-OF-STORE BREADTH</span><span class="ap-subtitle">Promo intensity · Supply chain · Level of service</span></div>
              <div class="ap-desc">The decisions made outside the store that land on the store as cost: promo complexity (ventes sans suite in FR, permanent discounts in ES), supply chain (case pack sizes, delivery frequency, misalignment between shelf layout and picking routes), and the service level trade-off. These are not visible from the shop floor — you have to look upstream.</div>
              <div class="ap-output">→ Workload model that links upstream decisions to in-store hours.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="approach-plus">+</div>
          <div class="approach-point">
            <div class="ap-badge ap-badge-a">↓</div>
            <div>
              <div class="ap-header"><span class="ap-keyword">IN-STORE DEPTH</span><span class="ap-subtitle">Productivity · Utilization · Process · Organization</span></div>
              <div class="ap-desc">What tasks are done, how, with what efficiency. Activity management (planning → task management → KPI loop). Process fixes that eliminate rework and overwork. Operating model and staffing mix (full-time, interim, uberized). We go down to L4/L5 level — seconds per task × product family — not just ratios.</div>
              <div class="ap-output">→ Benchmark at gesture level. TO-BE model. TimeSkipper-ready.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="approach-conclusion">Result: A TO-BE model that captures both what the store can fix and what HQ must fix to stop generating it.</div>
